## Mobile-first and Responsive Design

- Design components mobile-first: write base styles for small screens, then enhance with breakpoints (`sm`, `md`, `lg`, `xl`, `2xl`).
- Ensure excellent experiences on both mobile and desktop: test layouts, spacing, and interactions across common breakpoints.
- Prefer flexible layouts (grid/flex) and fluid widths; avoid fixed widths except at large containers.
- Maintain accessible touch targets on mobile (≥44x44px)
- Avoid hover-only interactions; provide focus/active alternatives.
- Optimize images for small screens by default; progressively enhance on larger screens.

Examples:

```typescript
// Mobile-first card that scales up responsively
const ResponsiveCard = () => (
  <div className="w-full max-w-full sm:max-w-md md:max-w-lg lg:max-w-xl bg-white rounded-xl shadow md:shadow-lg">
    <div className="h-40 sm:h-48 md:h-56 bg-gradient-to-br from-green-400 to-blue-500" />
    <div className="p-4 sm:p-6">
      <h3 className="text-lg sm:text-xl md:text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">
        Nombre del Sendero
      </h3>
      <p className="text-sm sm:text-base text-gray-600 mb-4 line-clamp-3">
        Descripción breve del sendero para pantallas pequeñas. Se expande en
        escritorios.
      </p>
      <div className="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between gap-3">
        <span className="text-sm text-gray-500">12 km</span>
        <span className="self-start sm:self-auto px-2 py-1 bg-blue-100 text-blue-800 rounded-full text-xs font-medium">
          moderado
        </span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
);

// Mobile-first grid that adds columns at larger breakpoints
const ResponsiveGrid = ({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) => (
  <div className="grid grid-cols-1 gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 xl:grid-cols-4">
    {children}
  </div>
);
```
